<p>Now, onto Jazzy bill. I was reading <a href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/31/what_do_we_mean_by_rationality/">What do we mean by â€˜Rationalityâ€™</a>, and ran across this:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Sometimes experimental psychologists uncover human reasoning that seems very strange - for example, someone rates the probability â€œBill plays jazzâ€ as less than the probability â€œBill is an accountant who plays jazzâ€.  This seems like an odd judgment, since any particular jazz-playing accountant is obviously a jazz player.  But to what higher vantage point do we appeal in saying that the judgment is wrong?</p>
