<p>I think that there might be a simple explanation for people saying this,
and it doesnâ€™t have to do with probability or decision theory overmuch. It has to do with the semantic domain of the sentence, or the Grician implicature. I donâ€™t know the actual words to use here, so Iâ€™m making them up as I go. Thatâ€™s ok, this is a formulation blog, and this post is already too long.</p>

<p>â€œBill plays jazzâ€ is pretty unambiguous, we can all agree. Thereâ€™s an
entity, <em>Bill</em>, such that he plays <em>jazz</em>. (If you want, you can imagine
Clinton on his saxophone here - I am, and itâ€™s rather amusing.)</p>

<p>What <em>is</em> ambiguous is â€œBill is an accountant who plays jazz.â€ Not
because of the referent of <em>who</em>, but because of the inability for the
written word to put the stress in the right place. Compare:</p>

<ol>
  <li><em>Bill</em> is an accountant who plays jazz.</li>
  <li>Bill is an <em>accountant</em> who plays jazz.</li>
  <li>Bill is an accountant, <em>who plays jazz.</em></li>
</ol>

<p>â€œwho plays <em>jazz</em>â€ would also be acceptable in 3.</p>

<p>Logically, rationally, if you were to formulate each of these down into
a formula (as above) they would all come out as less probable than â€œBill
plays jazz.â€ However, given the different readings, the mind can
construct worlds in which it is more plausible for 2 or 3 to occur
than 0 (or 1, which is pretty unambiguous too.) I donâ€™t mean creating
a specific scenario where all accountants play jazz and Bill is normally
associated with reggae-only assassins, not accountants. I mean, rather,
that (bear with me) with the statement that Bill is an accountant, with a
relative clause attached about jazz appended on, one is less likely to
view the relative clause as implausible. I think that this might occur
because the mind is more likely to accept a fictional world as truth
when more information is supplied, and that the more information, the
less people suspect that the other objects may in themselves be less
plausible. I suspect there is some truth in this.</p>

